n1: naked-eye appearances
	summary=What the senses give directly: dots, streaks, sunrise, seasons, and other local appearances that do not explain themselves.
n2: hidden cosmic reality
	summary=The real structure behind appearances: stars, galaxies, transmutation, deep time, and laws that no one observes directly.
n3: explanatory theory
	summary=A claim about what exists and how it behaves, used to make sense of appearances rather than copy them.
n4: empiricism
	summary=The false view that knowledge is derived from sensory experience, as if nature writes theories into the mind.
n5: sensory authority
	summary=Experience treated as a source of justification, replacing older authorities while keeping the same authority-shaped mistake.
n6: inductivism
	summary=The false view that repeated experiences can be generalized into scientific theories or reliable predictions.
n7: logical gap
	summary=No deduction from statements about experiences can reach truths about unseen reality, distant places, or future cases.
n8: conjecture
	summary=The creative origin of theories: minds rearrange and improve existing ideas before criticism and testing select among them.
n9: criticism
	summary=The error-correction pressure that asks whether an idea solves the problem without smuggling in arbitrary details.
n10: fallibilism
	summary=The stance that no source makes knowledge certain, so progress depends on expecting error and trying to correct it.
n11: theory-laden observation
	summary=Observation already contains interpretation; even recognizing repetition or evidence depends on prior explanatory ideas.
n12: problem
	summary=A conflict between ideas, expectations, or appearances that calls for a better explanation.
n13: background knowledge
	summary=Familiar explanatory assumptions that make rules of thumb look simple while quietly doing much of the work.
n14: rule of thumb
	summary=A narrow predictive habit that works in familiar cases but lacks reach without an explanation of why it works.
n15: instrumentalism
	summary=The false view that science only predicts observations and should not describe the reality causing them.
n16: realism
	summary=The view that physical reality exists and can be understood through rational inquiry and explanatory theories.
n17: bad explanation
	summary=An explanation easy to vary while still fitting the same appearances; it can absorb failure without real progress.
n18: good explanation
	summary=An explanation hard to vary because each detail does functional work; changing it breaks the account.
n19: testability
	summary=A valuable check when paired with good explanations, but not enough when theories are arbitrary or easily adjustable.
n20: tradition of criticism
	summary=A culture of carrying ideas forward by exposing them to objections instead of protecting them as authority.
n21: Enlightenment
	summary=The wider shift toward rejecting authority, seeking good explanations, and building institutions around criticism and progress.
n22: axis-tilt explanation
	summary=The seasons explained by Earth's tilted rotation relative to its orbit, where geometry and heat each matter.
n23: seasonal reach
	summary=The axis-tilt explanation applies beyond its original evidence: hemispheres, tropics, polar days, and other planets.
n24: knowledge growth
	summary=Sustained progress produced when conjectures meet criticism and good explanations replace static or parochial ideas.
n25: beginning of infinity
	summary=The open-ended possibility created by explanations with reach, especially under a tradition that keeps correcting errors.
